The Prague Stock Exchange finished with fewer points at the end of the day
After the morning's sharp fall, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
The transactions in ČEZ's shares reached approximately half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of trading Tuesday, reacted immediately to the fall of Monday when it fell to about 6%.
The decline this time is due to the fall in the stock on Wall Street.
It also expresses the market reaction to the outcome of the U.S. House of Representatives vote that refused to support the financial sector secretary's stabilization plan.
Asian equity falls
Asian stock markets fell dramatically on Tuesday, although the index eventually eased some of the losses throughout the day.
The Hang Seng Index of Hong Kong Stock Exchange throughout its trading day marked nearly four percent, although it later cushioned its losses by reducing the decline by practically 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movements of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell 3.8 percent, with Shanghai markets closed.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually the losses dropped to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange according to the Secretary of the Index fell to 3.6 percent.
"The rescue actions planned in the US are unsafe and this is influencing the financial market around the world", said the head of the Hong Kong Mint, Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it determines its monetary policy on its own, i.e. without dependency on the Central Bank of China.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
American lawmakers should reconvene as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that the falls will be felt in other countries.
Bloodbath of the American stock
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the plan to help the financial system, which should be allocated $700 billion.
The lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush's invitation to support their plan.
For Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, American stocks experienced a bloodbath and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell to nearly seven percent, a drop of a similar size last recorded in 1987.
The index fell before it was announced but as soon as it was shown that the proposal of the assembly was not going forward, the index began to fall freely.
Congress retreats: US government can inject $700 billion into the banks
The highest representatives of Congress and the government, President George W. Bush, agreed to a pact in broad terms of financial aid to the American financial system.
The vote will take place early next week.
American lawmakers caused a gap in the talks over the approval of the bailout in its form of aid to the American financial system in the amount of 700 billion dollars (approximately 12 trillion crowns).
However, it's not yet won.
Congressmen have to fine-tune some details of the contract before they can make public the final form of the law and have it voted on.
The financial system relief plan will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Services and Banking Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could be held in the Senate not before Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the rescue plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
But then the 'de-enchantment' will be achieved by the complex mechanisms which will also help the market in practice.
The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We resolved our differing opinions regarding the form of the package of measures for market stabilization", Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still be held on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met Sunday night with the finance minister, Henry Paulson, to give the government fund a definite shape.
The latter should buy from financial companies the unsold mortgage assets that lead financial companies to heavy losses and threaten the stability of the whole system.
"We are about to conclude the agreement on the plan, which will work and also must be effective in the market.
It is necessary to continue with the sanitation plan, but I think we are already on it", said Paulson.
A Signal to Asian Business
The global financial crisis is specifically affecting the rapidly falling stock market.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada, lawmakers are doing everything possible to get Congress to finally approve a deal this Sunday.
They want to reassure investors' businesses before the Asian financial market as these are the ones that are in the first time zone and where the Congress could influence the trade of Monday.
However, for now there is nothing clear with certainty about when the two houses of the American Congress will vote and, even, if they will not be stalled at the last moment with some problem.
Lawmakers believe it will be passed in the next few days.
The law, however, will undergo a series of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system should be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion must be made available as soon as possible, as requested by President George Bush.
However, Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its purpose, which would be another $100 billion and later the last $350 billion.
Bush appreciated the progress of the meetings
On the other hand, the president can veto this decision but Congress can override his veto by a majority vote.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program was to raise funds to buy back bad mortgage bonds whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to finish paying their mortgages.
"We worked everything.
The House of Representatives would have to be ready to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday", commented Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The American President Bush is also satisfied with the progress of the meetings.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and that he appreciated "both sides' efforts to stabilize our financial market and protect our economy".
Limitation of the shielded contract
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, head of the negotiators, said lawmakers decided on the responsibility of the program money for protecting taxpayers from its losses, a relief clause of the scheduled finance plan.
The new law should also limit so-called 'shielded contracts' for directors of companies participating in the programme, and create a committee which will have control of the Fund.
This would have to be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this, and we have made great progress towards a convention that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans", said Paulson.
The plan also includes help for homeowners who have problems with their payments.
The government would have to agree to new mortgage payments that it purchases in order to lower the monthly installment payments burden of debtors and enable them to keep their homes.
Marek: psychological support
The proposed plan is, according to Patria Finance's chief economist David Marek, a good idea that will be realized but rather difficult.
"And that is why it is not known with what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be bought.
This will be decisive for the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government", Marek said this week, for the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not, according to Marek, so relevant.
"Much more important is that, as early as this week, the congressmen agree to support it and give it their full approval as soon as possible.
This important and psychological agreement to get this approval is, at the moment, the most important thing", Marek insisted.
Hand-to-hand combat: the MP3 player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
Which seems clear that it's better to buy only the phone.
Yet there are enough reasons for man to acquire only the breeder.
The choice depends largely on the way it is used and on the requirements of the future owner.
It's probably going to be hard for me to get the most modern record player to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album on.
On the other hand, these kinds of musical products like LP records are no longer available, and as far as their quality is concerned, there is no objective reason to continue buying them.
If you have vinyl records on your shelves with art rock, jazz, or blues music, you are probably dreaming, at least, of this kind of record player.
This is the same with music that's on the way, which is compressed, simplified music -- MP3 music.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as it is for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try the 20-crown market helmets.
Two ends, between which there's enough room for each.
The choice is wide.
It also decides the battery life.
Some of the best players do much more than just play music and even that which even most of the mobiles do not.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the most basic functions like telephoning, texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera and can even navigate.
And when you take into consideration the smartphone and the PDAs, you're going to have in your pocket also a small computer.
This is a small miracle since no refrigerator knows how to grill and no television can take pictures.
The universality of mobile phones also brings us disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the sooner the indicator on your screen will light up asking to be recharged.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy drains.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simpler ones) clearly have a higher performance.
So, please note that cheap cell phones will not play for more than two hours.
If, in addition, you are constantly called on to get a charger for your work, this is also true for the most expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player this problem is not going to have, because even the worst ones hold at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, only some of the devices have a universal USB connector and, moreover, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly onto the memory card but only in some un-shrunken reader units can the small memory cards used in mobile phones be connected.
With the exception of some players (iPod), no special software is required.
Just fill the device with music through the computer's USB.
Most mobile phones and players create their own order in the music library according to the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to the user rating.
Some devices only display a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Explorer and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows best
When choosing a particular piece of equipment, take into account the battery's resistance, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of handling.
If he listens to music as a background and he listens to it every day for a short time, like in the tram, then he can use any mobile phone that plays.
Which practically any mobile really gets.
He should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile phone or the music player plays.
MP3 is played by everyone and practically all the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and excepting it the absolute majority of the apparatus play music in WMA format.
The less common ones include AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
The mobile internet is a simple way of visiting the relevant pages of the mobile operator (or any other service provider) and buying a song or album.
This service alone could be a compelling argument for acquiring a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is miserable and most are limited only to the themes of fleeting success of the radios.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally assumed that this particular way of selling music (whether by GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people have a cell phone with them at all times.
Whenever he wants to listen to something, he will find the phone in his pocket, while the MP3 player will be left at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or, at least, the handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has practically every mobile at least one MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobile phones with music will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three grand.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can buy a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the lack of a classic headphone jack.
The best ones, even in terms of the technical part, such as telephones equipped with a 3.5 mm input for classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing more than their ease of use.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are really handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, their handling similar to the previous cassettes or to the turntables is obvious.
It's not a threat in the sense that we accidentally connect to the internet with our mobile phone and, consequently, a gigantic data download bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example, the Vodafone 527) have as a general rule a slot for changing the memory card (M2 type, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a proper card, it will reach two thousand crowns.
Be careful, though.
The basic models are usually equipped with only a 2 GB card of maximum capacity.
Only the most expensive ones have 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, check out Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) no more than 1,100 kroner is needed.
If you are among the most demanding music lovers, you can use the most specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of a single player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman line of phones have almost identical use as a standalone MP3 player.
The same service and the same price category, about four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand mentioned above brings MP3 players.
The first virtual operator is due to arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer practically all the services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
He'll probably be here any minute.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to be reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper than those sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, you need competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, since we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has already stated that there is no longer any place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a conventional operator with its own network it no longer has many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find a frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant price drop, which also affected traditional operators.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market of Great Britain, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is a place for these types of operators and that they can succeed.
Other examples need not be looked for too far.
In February this year we reported on the launch of the mobile operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, Mobilking is backed by the Penta group, which is also the owner of U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order to operate effectively, they need to have far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not incur relatively large costs in building, operating and maintaining the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators usually profile themselves with low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages which however, is often countered with the offer of more adjusted services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a good bet to bet on a not trivial target group.
This operator is specifically targeting the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he is the operator you like and can trust", says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which runs the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as that of Poland could catch on in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, the service provision is relatively saturated".
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is to be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region", Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone conversation with mobil.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile phone operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to avoid any potential competition.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group which would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
'We have a great interest in this, to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators with this possibility.
With some of them we have managed to advance in meetings", said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then perhaps they spark better times.
It seems that, according to unofficial information, the first official operator should arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now, his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
'At the moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market is a very specific market compared to others.
So far no one has approached us with any complex and serious project in this field", Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is referred to by other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional agreement with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, mutually beneficial, can continue to develop".
He adds: "On T-Mobile's network it will be difficult to find any virtual carrier until the end of the year.
We should have some concrete contracts on the table at this point, which could be studied in such a short timeframe".
Vodafone is focusing on the requirements of a 3G licence.
The Commission considers that the aid is compatible with the internal market if it is compatible with the internal market within the meaning of Article 107 (3) of the Treaty.
We consider it to be the biggest contribution from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is to partner with a network to provide fast mobile internet".
Responsible offices - with the meat and nail operators
The progress of mobile operators is easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, which would lead to lower prices and, with them, lower profits.
So why make it easy to enter the competition?
When operators want to achieve something, they are able to pull a single string, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on ČTU was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by public information available on the CTU website.
But now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: 'In addition, the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened up to a fourth operator not long ago.
As regards the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player on the market would place high demands on it and, above all, on its services.'
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries.
This is purely the responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tendering (ÚOHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after an agreement on the lease of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
The Commission has not yet concluded any agreements with the potential bidders, which were not sufficiently attractive to the traditional operators", added Kristián Chalupa, from the external relations department of the ÚOHS.
These statements are not surprising to the representatives of the operators.
For the agencies which must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, it is also a matter of ensuring that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries where virtual operators operate normally, we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the decrease in prices of mobile telephone services"
The pressure on the proper functioning of the market and the lowering of prices are clearly not in the interest of OHIM.
What is really dramatically shocking in this whole case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence, it comes up by itself.
It is the same with the price of petrol at petrol stations, because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
'The Office has found no evidence of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore they do not have a corresponding increase in responsibility for their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunication regulators", Chalupa added to his answer.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of the many points of conflict.
There is clearly an analysis of relevant markets by the CTU that the telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge, agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for ÚOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are rising in a strikingly similar way.
The current complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they encounter many similar impediments.
Charging the ČTÚ with responsibility is a fairly common trick in the telecommunications field from which the ÚOHS washes its hands of this whole matter.
We've encountered him before in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act was recently introduced to extend the competence of the ČTÚ in the field of commercial tendering, but it was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be perfectly clear to the representatives of the UOHS, but their interests are clearly elsewhere.
Everything is fine when no one's looking
At the same time, it is still working in a sort of unnoticed virtual operator, which already exists in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that set their own prices for mobile telephony services, but only a part of them is public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally only a select few get the price list from these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will receive special prices and other offers afterwards.
The problem is that the commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If cases like the ones you mention were discovered, we could talk about infringement of the contract conditions which could lead to the end of the partnership with the company in question", Martina Kemrová replied to a question on this issue.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity by mobile operators would not reach people who are responsible.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers may be involved.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
The activities of these companies generate considerable profits and at the same time - unlike genuine virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of the potential problems: "the law allows such speculation, but the services of this company are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it at their disposal like a normal customer of the operators".
This is precisely what should seem to CTU to be at least a little strange.
There is also a new question for the SSSO.
If mobile phone operators turn a blind eye to this type of procedure, why do they block the entrance of the virtual operator?
It should be added that the OHIM has sufficient competence to detect this type of activity and if it is not willing it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this break-in.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, possibly, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the more advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in no case have they defended the operators but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual operator and with it, others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulator treats this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
We cannot but be impressed by our experience that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators let in a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
I listened to all four presentations of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Czech official celebrations day presented the new official recording of the anthem Dónde, mi hogar.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are solo, one with male and female voices, one with choir and one with instrumental.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
Radio Czech has said before that it intentionally chose for the Solos singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with both of them and then, also, with the Choir to look at the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it had consonance", he commented.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home was first played in 1834 at the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged to the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people embraced it.
The first stanza of the song after the rise of Czechoslovakia in 1918 naturally became part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
What's the "new" anthem sound like?
The Prague MHD takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, is written into the history of Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers board the subway, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
It can now be purchased by almost a hundred thousand people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously charge it to their chip card at the infocentres and transport company stalls at the Metro stations, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The vouchers can be bought online from yesterday on the transport company's website www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 people by the evening.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about the ticketing booths in the subway stations, where until now they had to regularly queue up to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is a window with staff who help interested people with online purchases and also with the recharge of the voucher purchased on their card", said the project spokesman, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to top up the electronic voucher in the Opencard at the vending machines in some metro halls.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, they remind us of a banknote machine and travellers will probably have already noticed them at the metro stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are five in the city now but by the end of the year there should be eighty", Opatrný added.
The bond is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Just insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
The electronic bonds are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, on the ring trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 which are used mainly by the inhabitants of the central Bohemian towns.
"In the trains belonging to the integrated transport of Prague there are controllers equipped with a card reader that will help to confirm the validity of the time and the zone of the bonus", explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that establishes the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
Bypass buses have their reading cards mounted in the driver's cabin.
When entering, it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany him with the Opencard in the place designated for this on the side of the Box.
The driver then checks the validity of the voucher.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than to request the driver this information", Drápal added.
Passengers who do not travel on the ring buses and do not remember when their voucher expires can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here on the machine screen, you will be shown information about the validity of your document.
The Southeast wanted to join the U.S. in a referendum.
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans demanded that Fumaba become part of the United States.
This is what is extracted from the letter which is kept in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With this wish, presumably, some groups of Sudeten Germans addressed the President of the United States in the year 1945.
It is from letters that are kept in a private archive and that are now kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov request in a letter to the American president not to allow the return of the "Sumava land" - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Pact - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want your word that the American units are coming to German lands not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators" is written in the letter, signed by "the people who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts".
In view of the fact that the union of Czechoslovakia with the south-eastern Germans presumably implies - according to them the Czech national character - a hope only in brutality, disregard, incomprehension, pressure and slavery, the authors urge in the letter to the American president to assume for today and forever Šumava under a protectorate.
"We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million inhabitants, we are handed over to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way collaborates with the victory of the allies", the letter writes.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is presumably fear of reprisals from the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president presumably doubted this idea of the Shumavian Germans, it would be enough to organize in the Shumavian lands a referendum on whether its inhabitants want to be part of the US or live under its patronage.
Although the letter's text, with our current knowledge of postwar history, may sound a bit childish, according to some experts it accurately portrays the expectations of the Germans of the southeast at the time.
Although the Czech Germans must have at least intuited that it was going to be about their expulsion from the republic only a few admitted this possibility.
Some hoped that the United States and Britain would negotiate for the Sudetes some clear form of autonomy.
Others thought they'd stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is even confirmed by the Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
He was in the war, as a German from Budějovice, enlisted in the Baltic navy.
When the British captured him at the end of the war and put him in the Holstein prison camp, dozens of Germans came to him to learn Czech.
"They thought that when they returned home, the check would come in handy", Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners who lived before the war in Czechoslovakia, according to him, expected that on the basis of the Bennes Decrees they would be removed from the Republic.
