Rats have feelings too.
They say that a rat or a cockroach, feeling danger, runs away, why is it also afraid?
Neuroscientist Joseph Le Doux is convinced that many animals have feelings too.
How can we control if they, behaving in a way similar to us, feel the same way?
An Internet magazine called "Edge" has been publishing the contributions of famous scientists for many years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question What do you think is true without being able to prove it?
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else could not prove until now, although we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case at least we can expect it because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as soon as we go to other species and include questions about sensation and about consciousness in general, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware doesn't match.
When a rat is in danger, it does what all other animals do - it acts dead, runs away, or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists draw conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
I don't think so, of course.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to pass on our subjective experience to that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated with human consciousness in the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (because of their involvement in short-term memory and executive functions that direct behavior).
This broad part is far more developed in the case of humans than in that of other primates and seems to be absolutely lacking in other creatures.
Considering at least the aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex, including knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to suppose that even man is different from other primates.
Another peculiarity is found in man's linguistic nature: Since most of his experience is bound up with language, that often means that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would influence it so that the consciousness of animals, created however, would in many cases differ from most of our states of consciousness.
So it's hard to explain how the consciousness of other animals works.
If that, as something interesting and subjective, can't be measured because it has special hardware, can't be analyzed by our experiences, then your research presents us with big problems.
Most of my talks are about the content of conscious experience, but at the same time there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be easier for scientific research.
You could investigate the conscious processes of animals without regard to their contents, and that's what happens during short-term memory studies of primates, especially in the visualization example.
But with this approach that Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, the essential thing passes rather to the neutral correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: The two may or may not be similar.
Interestingly, this approach highlights the importance of the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex for the formation of visualization.
And what does that do for sensations?
I owe it to the fact that in the emotional system, a part of the brain is activated that is responsible for that, the same thing that happens with fear.
What we describe as fear is therefore a state of mind in which we are when the activity of the brain occupies a space of the defense system (or its consequences such as for example the reactions of the body).
From this point of view, sensations are very much fixed in the cerebral cortex, which is what distinguishes primates and especially man.
From the point of view of linguistic nature, fine sensory classifications follow because we can differentiate and classify states with the help of words and grammar to be able to describe the states of others on par with ourselves.
For example, Antonio Damasco, on the contrary, thinks that sensations are derived from simple activities of the parts of the cerebral cortex responsible for bodily feelings and the brain stem, and Jaak Pankseep thinks the same, but focuses more on the brain stem.
Because this network hasn't changed much during human evolution, it can refer to absolutely different types and their sensations.
For theoretical reasons I cannot go against that, but I consider it unlikely.
Pakseep argues that what rats and men feel as fear, possibly that is felt in two cases also like this: But how can it be controlled if rats and men behaving similarly feel the same?
Seeing danger, a cockroach runs away, but because it's afraid?
I am of the opinion that the similarity of behavior does not yet prove the similarity of experience.
That's true that the neuronal comparison helps: rats and men have similar brainstems, cockroaches on the contrary do not have at least one brain.
Is the brain stem responsible for sensation?
Even though it's possible to test it for men, how can you test it for rats?
I think that rats and other mammals, possibly also cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how you can prove it.
I prefer to research rat emotional behavior rather than emotional sensations because their sensations are supposedly fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is about special circuits and language).
In any case, progress in the field of neurology is expected here, as the same measurements are taken of rats and men.
Because I don't investigate rat language and consciousness, as well as sensations, I don't know if they exist.
