However, the open question for Mr Obama is whether the commitment to bilingual education, which prefers classroom instruction in languages other than English, is effective in overcoming the distance in the final outcomes.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an officially recognized elementary school in the eastern region of Los Angeles County.
At this school, the vast majority of students are Hispanic and from low-income families:
More than a third of the students, many of them newcomers, are learning the English language.
However, an incredible 100 percent of fourth-year students have been positively evaluated in the 2008 math test.
And an equally astonishing 93 percent have mastered the English Language and Arts test.
This incredible success has been achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama's favorite.
Sixth Street emphasizes revision and practice, constant evaluation of competence and no tolerance for any apologetic attitude.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, the Sixth Street principal, the school's approach to teaching English to students is "full immersion".
Immersion in English means the almost exclusive use of the language in the handling of the instructional content.
Mrs. Mikels, who is opposed to bilingual education, told me, "We've had extraordinary success with students like this one who has come from Mexico and that, if you come into the classroom 12 months later, you wouldn't be able to pick up what was".
