The interior wants the driver with three administrative penalties for alcoholism, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting drunk, or if it does not blow.
The initiative was announced last June and is now included in the annual report of the State Attorney General's Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose of the training is to reintegrate the driver, who will also receive a course of road reeducation.
The experience will involve the Attorney General's Office for Road Safety, the Directorate General of Traffic (DGT) and the Foundation Technological Institute for Automobile Safety (FITSA).
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists who have been reported more than once for drunk driving take the car again.
The alcolock would prevent this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow out; or when a concentration of alcohol is detected is greater than the permitted.
The cost is more than €1,000 and would be borne by the sanctioned party.
A study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with these devices reduce infringements by up to 65% during the first year of implementation.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people each year.
The measure is linked to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means, and, however, the necessary reform by the criminal means requires a reform in an organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although it has already been experimentally implemented in some industrial and public service vehicles.
