Talking in my sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don't mean these people who wake up very excitedly telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk in their sleep.
The first time it happens, you might be a little freaked out, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a benign sleep disorder called somnaloquio.
It's quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one of you has heard that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often associated with other sleep disturbances, such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting, or sleepwalking, but this need not be the case.
As we have already mentioned, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation.
It's an understudied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a low voice, use loose words, murmur, or do the opposite (scream, cry, long speech, etc.).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, the child should be observed and a specialist consulted to check whether there is any issue that is causing great anxiety and giving it a way out.
We have said that it is a benign disturbance, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disturbance that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress pattern).
What you can do is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to bed.
So seek out quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who have great difficulty in relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will help the child to have a more restful sleep.
Once the sleepwalking starts, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
