Sarkozy finds the fishermen furious
Before departing for the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will take a detour around Brittany.
The President of the Republic decided to go to the port of Guilvinec, in the Finistère, on Tuesday morning to meet his representatives.
They promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that he "will come with concrete proposals".
This presidential visit coincides with the general meeting of the "crisis committee" created by the Breton fishermen to obtain measures against the increase in the prices of diesel, which marks a record by reaching 1,14 euros per liter.
According to the spokesman of the Elysee David Martinon, the president "will discuss with them solutions that can be imagined to help their companies to become competitive again and to save the conditions of employment and remuneration of the sailors".
The fishermen are waiting for Nicolas Sarkozy to come to the surface.
On Tuesday morning, they carried out operations to reduce traffic in Morbihan and Calvados, which have caused almost 10 km of traffic jams.
The Quiberon marina has also been blocked, but connections to Belle-Île have not been stopped.
A "filter barrier" has been put in place on the Quiberon peninsula.
The sailors showed their determination on Monday by burning tires and wooden pallets in front of the fuel tanks in the ports of Brest and Lorient, while demonstrations took place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic coast and the English Channel, such as Les Sables d'Olonne, in Vandea, where the bous stayed in the port, or in Le Havre, where some twenty ships blocked the movements of the merchant ships.
The fishermen of La Turballe and Croisic in the Loire-Atlantic region stopped the blockade of the important Total refinery in Donges in the afternoon.
The fishermen of Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait until the meeting of this Wednesday that will take place at the ministry to think about eventual actions.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" will have to think on Tuesday about the development of the movement and its participation in the planned meeting at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by officials from the national fisheries committee, which did not support their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen did not give up" and "they do not want to move towards Paris", announced for example Liliane Cariou, the chairman of the Lorient fisheries committee.
Professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently pay around 50 cents per litre but believe that a ship can reach financial equilibrium only with diesel priced below 0.30 euro per litre.
