The interview - blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday its 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most efficient blood suppliers in the world.
And most of all, he regained the public's trust that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood supply administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service has been contaminated with Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In view of this tragedy and the public's dissatisfaction, the Canadian government held a public inquiry in February 1994, presided over by Judge Horacio Krever, to clarify the circumstances that had led to this tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not be repeated.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his report, certain provinces then created a committee whose goal was to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all the other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system", recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After making a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained the public's trust", he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr Décary, however, points out that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing the emergence in Europe of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We are therefore relying on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, namely that when we do not know and when a serious disease can result from this, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we should introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we refused blood from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But some years ago, it was proved beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense".
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow the presence of the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors, rather than the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used up to now were based.
The nucleic acid tests shortened the time between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses could be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explained.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We can substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without us knowing and that we won't be able to detect them.
These improvements made it possible to reduce considerably the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in every 12 million is at risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV.
"That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before anyone is infected with HIV.
So since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission from a blood product occurs.
I believe that today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain health without worry", says the head of the Héma-Québec administration.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion. Like West Nile virus, it is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
"The needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Since anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which comprises on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate blood".
All healthy people over 18 years of age who meet the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled in a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Misery is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it's hard to get people to donate their blood, but especially to keep them and to encourage them to be regular donors.
Since life is so unrestrained today, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood", laments Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for the great burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases like leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, the bank placement of our thousandth cord blood sample and are expected to draw over a thousand of these per year.
We should start proposing it for grafts early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this", since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
