Free speech - the Orwellian discourse of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice-president and director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the largest gold company in the world has filed a six million euro defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of persecution for defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dared to hold a position contrary to his?
The outcome of the case is of little importance, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal arms, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is often to bankrupt the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will muzzle the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to reexamine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of the public that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by the exchange of ideas and not by the strokes of the garrote.
It was therefore enough for the mining company to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the question.
But Barrick Gold seems to distrust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for Noir Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can call for a "public" debate while disregarding the views of the public?
The Vice-President said that the word seems to refer only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, the opponents also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand, or does not want to understand, is that the public who support the authors and editors of Noir Canada do so primarily because they reject the brutal way of the mine.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized arguments, and not in the framework of what many people perceive as a persecution-bite (persecuting the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a request with respect to the authors of Noir Canada, intimating them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surrealist rhetoric, the Barrick Gold trial is a direct attack on the freedom of academic pursuit and the pursuit of truth, which are essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the basis of intellectual work.
