What was produced at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Very soon, on October 8, the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant damage, in a business manner, continuously and in an organized way in addition to other crimes, including the forgery of documents.
According to the prosecution, they used the funds obtained in public tenders for their own purposes, often justifying the fulfillment of the tasks with false invoices.
The public and municipal funds - in total some HUF 65 million - were partly deposited in the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation and partly in the pockets of private individuals.
The method, which was also revealed by the investigators, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the various associations never fulfilled their assumed obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the invoices were fake.
The stamps were obtained from the Józsefváros District market and the circular stamps were manufactured in the town of Kiskunhalas.
The question of which company was to be the counterfeit invoice was decided, among other things, during the visit to the Upper Balaton region to which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for invoices for his consumption and these served as a model to make the invoices that they presented among others in the contests of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labor Affairs, as well as in the City Hall of the Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information wrote the reports needed to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and its accomplices, this food centre provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However, according to the center's manager, there is not enough room for all of these people at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
For a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and no more than ten people could stay there in one night, yet the bill contained one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of fancy invoices also exaggerated when they pointed to the catering centre Pigal Kft. because in the bookkeeping of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he already knew that these were fake documents.
"Our company name and the NIF number were wrong on the stamp".
He added that in addition to the formal problems, he also did not agree that according to the bill a hundred people were accommodated, since they have only eleven rooms in which not so many people can fit.
Besides, the bill included meals, and the restaurant hasn't been open for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice manufacturers were also not informed that the chosen travel agency in Budapest organises exclusively trips abroad, so that they foolishly indicated on the cash invoice a trip within Hungary as a service, which also did not coincide with the invoice issuing practice of the agency.
In addition, as was found during the investigation, the document also included VAT, even though travel outside the European Union was exempt from tax.
The VAT measurement was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the services of that company are not charged with 25 but only 15 per cent VAT, and the hotel staff only issued invoices made by machine but the invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the "expedidores" made other mistakes as well, such as in the case of a company in which they put in the invoice as an activity carried out the transport by road which - it became known during the investigations of the prosecution - is not carried out by the company founded as an investment consultant.
The fact that the invoices were issued for Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont were also found to be false because of formal differences - the invoice was not in the correct format, the stamp was false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued these invoices.
The falsifiers also did not pay attention to the fact that when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group dined there (2001) Nyíregyháza HIB Kft. was in the process of liquidation, which is why the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
They consciously sent the invoices
Another group of manufacturers of false invoices are those who were aware that they should issue false invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice in the amount of approximately HUF 4 million in the name of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of Collab Kft. - according to the prosecution - was convinced by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
Zuschlag and its accomplices also collaborated with Biogate Kft., currently in liquidation, which in 2003 supplied invoices worth approximately HUF 5 million to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, with no real economic activity behind.
There was no movement of capital either, because later they canceled the prepared invoices but forgot to state in their documents to this entity.
The next group of forged invoice manufacturers includes those who have some connection with the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the defendant against the Ukrainian manager of Delta Trio SL, which had a fictitious registered office in Budapest and was engaged in the trade in fuel and vehicles.
This company issued numerous invoices in October, November and December 2005 for the sale of computer media, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation data these invoices were purchased by Cash Investment Kft. from Kiskunhalas, which since 14 September 2005 is under liquidation process.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov should have also dispatched the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices for the Atlasz, for the Hoppá and for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány in the name of the company, collecting the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies operated effectively because - according to the accused - they did not receive work.
But he took advantage of these companies, because at the request of his accomplice, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the company's registration documents, issued invoices in the name of the companies for the organizations linked to Zuschlag: for the Atlasz and for the Y-Generáció.
Kubatov, on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, issued a total of 15 invoices to different entities for a total value of HUF 14,2 million.
The Prosecutor's Office considered that Kubatov received VAT and 10% of the invoices.
That man even took advantage of the Szi-Beri partnership to issue fictitious invoices used in the Biztos Pont contest.
The Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért presented a competition in January 2006 to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility entity of the Socialist Party.
They obtained HUF 500 thousand respectively from the tender, but did not use the money for the purposes of the tender.
In order to avoid detection, they submitted to the TMA five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft.
These were the invoices found during the office search that Árpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Some of the accused will probably tell at the trial - as they did at the Prosecutor's Office - the course of the forgery of the invoices.
The most interesting thing is the confession of the main accused János Zuschlag himself, if he decides to dismantle everything.
For his confessions so far have not been very detailed and although he repeatedly promised to talk about everything, this has not been done so far.
The question is: what is the point of doing so, because perhaps in exchange for the return of the bulk of the money - fifty million HUF - the socialists reached an agreement with him so that Zusi would take all the responsibility.
Who, on the other hand, for these days could even be offended, since to alleviate his prison conditions he requested house arrest, but was repeatedly denied.
While the numerous perpetrators of economic crimes of very high value, who never returned the money, walk free or at least can wait in their own home for the sentence, he has no chance for that.
The psychology of over-simplification: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neuroscientists and economists at NYU have discovered the neurological-economic basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study in the journal Science, people don't want to lose out on competitions like eBay auctions, so they'd rather pay even an exorbitant price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in an auction, and the active areas of the participants' brains were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called the stratum located below the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to the scientists, the increase in the stakes is explained as a prevention to avoid provoking an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists in the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and they gambled.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
The third group, on the other hand, received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the group members lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that one was highlighted for success and the other for failure.
However, testing the hypothesis of the neurologists, members of the "failure" group were willing to bet even more than members of the control and "winner" groups.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For until now, the auction phenomenon has been explained solely by the joy of winning and the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so that we now arrive at a third explanation" - stated Andrew Schotter, professor at the Faculty of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor
Around five hundred million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are receiving treatment because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for a number of liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar, liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause are very different.
Pathogen-dependent hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through food (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal fluid, saliva).
Travellers are advised to protect themselves by vaccination against A and B viruses, there are no vaccines against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating the infected food, and are manifested by a bad general condition, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and on the whites of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, the urine dark in color, and healing can take up to two - three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten of those infected receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people who are infected do not know they are sick because this pathogenic agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms do not appear until 20 or 30 years later.
So early detection, systematic medical monitoring is very important.
Three groups are far more common: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattoo wearers.
Today, about 200 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can be detected with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease is curable if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so that the contagion can be suppressed and the cancer prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by representative organizations of the sick.
It aims to draw attention to the causes of chronic viral liver infections and the importance of early detection.
Does it hurt less for those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent study, religious faith has a calming effect that was also relieved by the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to examine how religious belief influences human pain, reports Britain's Telegraph newspaper.
In this unique experiment, 12 Catholic believers and an equal number of atheists were given electric shocks while they all looked at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, the Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of investigations in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University participate alongside academics.
The analysis was as follows: a sparkler was attached to the patient's left hand, which was given an electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants to fix their gaze on two paintings: the 17th-century Virgin Mary by Sassoferrato and the 15th-century Lady of the Snows by Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, who chose the oil of Leonardo because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a calming effect.
The patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while looking at the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics claimed that by looking at the Virgin Mary they felt "safe" as "protected" persons, "calmed down and had peace in their hearts".
When looking at the religious-themed painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when looking at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image that is so impactful, you can get a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, like a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases does change our personality", Wright added.
After these formidable results, only one question remains: What effect would it have on pain regulation if the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his stature were shown to the faithful?
Would a vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
You are what you say you are.
On its 10th birthday, Google can say: You can find it in people's pockets as well as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they've spent their holidays, which doctors they've visited and what interests they have.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, the skeptics who make a parallel with the Orwellian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect as much personal data about its users as possible, and this is necessary to be able to fulfill the original goals of Google's founders: "gather all the information in the world in one system!"
According to the head of Google, the company even after ten years of work that turned the world upside down is still in the initial phase of the commitment to be able to process all information.
To the question of what will happen in five years, Schmidt answered this: I would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What would be the job that would suit me best?" - however, software will not be able to answer such seemingly simple questions as long as there is not enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their Internet browsing, the searched keywords, IP addresses and pages they went to when they finished their search are stored with precision.
Thanks to Personalized Search, for example, which debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can re-consult what they searched before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - in this same logic will be based the Recommendations, in which the system will offer us products and services based on the previously defined and stored preferences.
What will happen if they use my data against me, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who are concerned about Google's information monopoly.
In most cases it is the potential represented by the company that can be feared rather than remorse, fear of punishment, longing for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that they not only keep, but in justifiable cases also give to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most discussed example of recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google gave the Brazilian government the information of its Web page, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
However, netizens who care about people's rights were relieved in May when the company along with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully proved to the court that it was right in its dispute with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google cannot be forced by any of the constitutional provisions to provide any type of information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government managed to obtain under the guise of enforcing the child protection law passed years ago, nearly fifty thousand web addresses and about a thousand search phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of web pages and keywords for the last two months.)
So there is a contradictory opinion about Google: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy is harmed, their private life by starting to use Google services, and they rebel against it as against the multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the North American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not so its rival, the Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the world, much as both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free software package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks see with precision the very problematic relationship between people's rights and the Internet that has been brought about precisely by one of the most talked about keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of the communication channels available, and while the measurement of these varies individually, the essence remains the same: to show ourselves.
A normal teenager can have profiles on numerous social media sites, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them to other services, such as Twitter or last.fm, which lists their music habits, then adds them to a tracking system like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and has a blog, where the latest photo galleries are automatically displayed, such as those stored on Flickr or Picasa.
We can know many cases where it becomes clear that for example the bride, by seeing the flow of photos of the next morning of common friends, finds out who spent the night before her fraudulent boyfriend or they can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion in his blog about the direction of the company: one thing is certain, the definition of private life has been completely revalued.
A person's online life is what they show about themselves - this is the definition behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least wants to avoid Google's monopoly, can do so (starting for example with the Scroogle that uses Google's search system, but leaves no traces).
There are many people who don't want to register on the collective pages to avoid being found, but you can replace the Google "online" applications, from the text writing software to the image and news reading applications with alternative versions that do not connect to giant servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
The public is almost openly waiting for the day when Google shows its true face.
