The smart car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What better way to develop collision avoidance technologies than by imitating the obstacle sensors found in nature?
Like the one with the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C robotic car steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space which actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained at the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
The compound eyes of bumblebees, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of over 300 degrees, play an important role.
To replicate the function of the compound eyes, engineers used the laser-beam length measurement system.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle's microprocessor which immediately transforms into a collision avoidance maneuver.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle's robot mimics the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by rotating the wheels to the required extent.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the vehicle robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Lab and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should mirror what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process must be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike the bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to avoid other bumblebees, here only used as a possibility for the robot of the auto the rotary movement and acceleration in addition to the braking.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries which are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life span than lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh says that the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the ability to process data, much less the ability to store it.
This apparatus must process only a few incoming signals every second and react accordingly.
There is no need to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
You don't need gigabytes of memory, you don't need megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, within ten years will be incorporated into mass-produced models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, bypassing the obstacles in his way.
