The written version of the law of the financial rescue package of 700 billion dollars has been prepared which will be implemented in several phases with the purpose of buying the bad loans of the banks.
Half the money will be spent in the first phase.
According to Eastern Time during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion financial rescue package in total, after several days of discussion - Reuters reported.
We have made important progress, said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic leader of the US Congress, saying that all that was left was to formalize the agreement in a document.
The commitment made on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise said: this program will work and will be efficient but other measures are needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the economy's wheel.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, i.e. on Sunday before 8 p.m. Washington time (or before 2 a.m. on Monday, Central European time), without causing a spectacular jump in the stock markets.
The so-called Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008 bill will be voted on Monday first by the U.S. Congress and then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
The program is different from the original Bush administration proposal to spend all of the $700 billion to buy bad credit union securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum the Treasury will buy bonds, bad-rated credit-fund securities, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This programme will be controlled by a special body, in which the Federal Reserve Chairman will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion can be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and securities of credit fund securities, in addition other loans of the "poisonous" type as well.
The purchase can be made at auction or directly - informed competent people of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the portfolio finance guarantees the worrying items, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
The law thus secures the necessary financial means, which can reach even 700 billion dollars to meet the urgent needs of the North American financial system, whether it be the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We are doing everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed - he added.
On the other hand, the heads of banks in difficulty and awaiting help from the State will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensation, which the American slang calls simply golden parachutes.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and the limits depend on the form of support from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys under an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on the gold parachutes, unless the failed bank's head retires.
By directly buying up bad loans the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that bosses' compensation is not overstated.
In addition to the above, the existing contracts for gold parachutes will not be changed, the limitations refer only to new contracts in order to stimulate participation in the programme.
This is the first case in American history that a legal limitation on the income of the CEOs will be in force - said the measure, the Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional committee responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the programme, thus reducing the risk for taxpayers, since they may even make a profit from the transaction once the economy recovers and with it the bank.
According to the bill, in the next five years the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to return to the taxpayers the losses of the financial sector.
Of course, there were reservations on both sides about the project.
This is not what the American citizens have entrusted to us, that is, taxpayers' dollars are not being protected - declared the Republican congressman from California, Darrell Issa.
His Ohio Democrat colleague, Mary Kaptur, claimed the measures were urged by the very people responsible for the Wall Street meltdown.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008 the national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the prices of the previous month and by 12.9 percent compared to the prices of the month of August 2007 - reported the Central Statistical Office (KSH).
Industrial export prices increased by 1,1% compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3,9% compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent from the previous month and by 3.2 per cent from the previous year.
Industrial selling prices rose only marginally, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic selling prices in the manufacturing sectors increased slightly by 0.1 percentage points compared with July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices was recorded in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2,8%) primarily due to the increase of 4,6% per month in bags and belts and the increase of 2,5% in footwear.
The higher price level of plastics and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical materials production branch (1.6 per cent).
There was a fall in prices in the petrochemical sector (1.4%), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9%), and - to a very small extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1%).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
The other sectors of the manufacturing industry recorded price increases of between 0.2 and 0.9%.
The supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which account for a significant proportion of internal trade, increased by 0.3% in August, mainly as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the sectors of the processing industry - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
The metalworking sector saw an increase of 13.2%, while the leading food, beverage and tobacco industry saw an increase of 11%.
Prices fell in the textile industry (2.5%) and in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3%).
In the other processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
During the past year, prices in the processing industry worldwide increased by 10.2 percent.
Prices for electricity, gas, heat and water supplies were 18.7 percent higher than last year.
In August, among the various sectors of domestic trade, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
Prices in the consumer goods sector increased by 0.3%, while prices in the energy sector and in intermediate sectors were unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increases compared to the same month of the previous year occurred in the energy and intermediate industry sectors (16.8%).
The consumer goods industries declined by 6.8 per cent and investment goods by 1.4 per cent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1,1% compared to the previous month and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3,9%.
The value of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
