Járóka: We must break the vicious circle of poverty and segregation
The European Summit on Equal Opportunities has started in Paris today, hosted by France, which is also this year's acting President of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, Member of Parliament for the European People's Party (Fidesz), in her speech to the plenary, as one of the main speakers at this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations of Roma children and also the biggest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, the European social partners and representatives of the most important European organizations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of MEPs in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, the Roma are excluded from the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"The majority of young Roma have not completed secondary education and, because of the poor quality of basic education, only a negligible proportion can obtain a university diploma".
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, plays a key role in ensuring that other human rights prevail.
Investment in educating Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
The Commission's proposal for a directive on the protection of the environment against the adverse effects of certain substances on the environment is a very important one.
The earlier a Roma student starts school, the more chances he has to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and the abolition of segregated and low-quality education", Lívia Járóka said.
The Commissioner for Education, Mr Jean-Claude Pompidou, said that the Commission had already taken the initiative to set up a European network of schools and colleges.
'We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, and give Roma children the chance to be part of a democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens,' Járóka said.
The European Summit on Equal Opportunities, which has been held annually since last year's Berlin meeting to mark the 'European Year of Equal Opportunities', aims to provide a unique forum for promoting the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and Member State level.
