The Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already been manifested a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 million bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans were, and are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
We have confirmation from yesterday's New York Times reporting that the ongoing crisis is disarming the Republican Party, ever more divided between its old soul of the East Coast, moderate, supportive of federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, on the other hand, conservative, hostile to those in Washington and the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, in fact, that has become arrogant with the voice of the one who spoke in the beginning.
The above is just one example of the changes, the great changes, that the economic earthquake now taking place is bringing about, not only in the United States but throughout the West, and not just here.
Both in the United States and in Europe, the crisis has long acted as an accelerator of incubation phenomena which, with the new climate, solidify and emerge.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary reactivation, of the dual category of state-sovereignty in relation to a type of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions which have, yes, strong financial relations with the outside world, but above all, the balance sheets of families living in a single country and in a single state are much more compromised.
The one which immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the hardship and protests of those people and those families who, on the other hand, are voters.
The crisis is global economically but it is national politically and exclusively.
Political internationalism seems to be substantially out of the question or they have little to say: the crucial test is the European Union, which, as always, is divided between different interests and different state strategies and is unable to decide on any common policy.
It is from the government of each state that everyone expects an intervention, rescue and reactivation plans, new rules and above all the subsidization of funds: from the moment you reach the court it is only the state that has the economic resources and the mass of financial resources to remedy things.
And they also have the means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of incalculable value, values which under certain circumstances no market and no organisation will probably ever be able to dispose of in the same measure.
This new emphasis on the nation state in the crisis is in perfect harmony with the greater importance that the new development of the economy tends to attribute to a factor closely linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the web of ever more sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to dominate the world, we realized that our future would instead have to do more and more with the little immaterial things like water, crops and oil.
All things that, look, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth but are equally united in an absolute way in a circumscribed space, a territory.
So whoever finds himself as sovereign, certainly holds many more cards than whoever is not, and who has the misfortune of living in a post without crops, without oil and without water.
I get to the second novelty, but it's a sign of a fracture.
Who says territory, state, government, inevitably says politics and leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the objective awareness of the need for leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take the situation in hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discrediting of the existing leadership, of economically inadequate relief with many dark areas.
And together something deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an intolerance, an inappropriate image, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class of the countries of the West in growing numbers.
It seems to advance more and more, in various places of the population, the conviction that rather than their actions are the same as those of the social elites so far in the boom, the same way of feeling and being, their culture in the comprehensive exception of the term, to have made their own time and to be more alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in a nutshell, is feeding underground a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in an "electoral revolt" or in the sudden shifts in collective moods of recent times, from the conservative exit in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the social democratic consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the men of the American congress against Bush (and also coincides with the victory of the right in Italy that has something to do).
It seems to me that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, some would say, make it increasingly difficult to understand and then to represent what is now taking shape in the deep layers of Western society and which the economic crisis is renewing, increasing and potentially shaking to the limit.
In the face of all this, to speak of a "mass rebellion" today is frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not.
