When energy is born from waves, the great ones come on stage
It's an extinct deposit that covers over 70% of the surface of the planet and it's being discovered now by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources that the big guys like Chevron are looking at.
The possibility of harvesting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70s together with the first oil crisis, the research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put on the backburner, but now that environmental issues and the new oil surge are giving the sector a boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated that by 2007, 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by implants that exploit the movement of ocean waves.
This would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants today.
And then there'd be the currents and the tides.
Giants to the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an installation in the north of Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away from betting on marine energy are always more and among these companies those who have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology", a spokesman for a company associated with the US oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is looking into the possibility of cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the US energy commission to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It is a rather important sign, considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to drill for new oil.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are following the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed, indicates a rising interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts say the technology is still in its infancy, because there is no doubt that marine energy has a huge environmental impact.
So far, impacts like the Portuguese or the Scottish are small and don't seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, you have to use a technology with a greater environmental impact.
And there are a number of options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected together.
The force of the waves, which moves the boas up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside the boas.
The pressure turns a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
The electricity is sent to the shore through underwater cables.
There are currently four implants of this type under development, awaiting federal approval alone, aside from the energy, it could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot, using subsea turbines on New York's East River.
The movement of water when there are tides, causes the turbine blades to spin, creating a rotational motion that powers the generator.
Verdant has said that he has a long list of clients waiting for the necessary permits to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, say the Institute for the Development of Electric Power, is the potential of tides at this time.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It's mainly about tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others that are approaching the coast, have invested 7.5 million dollars in 2008 and are planning an investment of 35 million for 2009.
